Is the suggestion that something like...
```
const ObjectPrototype = Object.getPrototypeOf({})
const ValuePrototype = Object.getPrototypeOf(value);
if(null === ValuePrototype || ObjectPrototype === ValuePrototype) {
  return true;
}
return false;
```
...could be return false for otherwise "plain objects" in certain contexts?

It still feels weird, since when can prototypes be recursive or exist twice in a prototype chain?  They can't (or the loop might go forever sometimes, right?) – so asking if this looped `proto === Object.getPrototypeOf(value)` (as we call this root-prototype object) is really equivalent to asking `Object.getPrototypeOf(Object.getPrototypeOf(value)) === null`.

To rephrase, it makes no sense to ask if `Object.getPrototypeOf(value) === proto` and assume our while-loop looped 6-7 times to find `proto`, when it was coming from `value` in the first place – right?  No, the only thing it'll ever do is loop once – unless I'm missing something about recursive prototypes etc.

I suppose it could be more like...
```
if(!value) {
  return false;
}
const maybeRootPrototype = Object.getPrototypeOf(value);
if(maybeRootPrototype === null) {
  return true;
}
return Object.getPrototypeOf(maybeRootPrototype) === null && maybeRootPrototype.constructor === value.constructor;
```
I mean when else can a prototype be null except for a "contexted" root-level `Object` and `Object.create(null)`?

