I found myself in situations that required a logic similar to this `afterEvery` on two previous occassions and they were my main motivation for creating this, @zaclummys.

1. I had a long running process which had a few hundred lines of console output. It was a set of very verbose ansible playbooks developed by multiple people. I wanted to monitor the process but without the hundreds of colourful console logs. Long story short, I piped the output and displayed every Nth line.
2. I was working on an app and I wanted the user to be able to set notification settings to be notified after 'Every 5 incoming messages', 'Every 10 incoming messages' and 'Every 25 incoming messages.'

Some use cases that I can think of right now are:
1. If you want to display every Nth incoming data element in a stream
```javascript
var notify = afterEvery(5, (data)=> {
      console.log(data.message)
})
stream.on('data', (data) => {
  notify(data)
})
```

2. If one uses a randomizing logic: randomizing after every N calls, wherever possible, could be a more efficient strategy than for every call/iteration
```javascript
let a = Math.random()
let ran = afterEvery(4, () => {
      a = Math.random()
})
for(var i=0; i<20; i++)
{
    ran()
    console.log(a)
}
```

3. Along the same lines, if one wants to use a key from a pool of keys for making API calls for N number of calls and then pick another key from the pool, `afterEvery` can be used.

