@jdalton After thinking about it more, shallow cloning a `view` type seems pointless - because you can't do:

``` js
// !!!! Non-example/pattern
var section1 = _.clone(dv);
section1.byteOffset += 1024;
var section2 = _.clone(section1);
section2.byteOffset += 1024;
```

I can't think of a real use-case for shallow cloning a `DataView`
If I want to clone the buffer, I'll do that.

But if I want to clone a DataView, **surely I mean to get a new DataView w/ a copy of the visible buffer?**

``` js
// so in code-words:
var dv1 = _.clone(someDataView);
// Is almost no different than doing this:
var dv1 = someDataView;
// DataView members are immutable after all
```

That would be consistent with the spread operator as well:

``` js
let fn = (...args) => args;
fn(undefined, 42, undefined);
```

(these examples are not covering arrays intances on the arguments)

