```

It would keep the nulls at the beginning and still allow sorting:

``` js
_.sortBy(['b', null, NaN, 'c', undefined, null, undefined, NaN, 'a'])
// => [null, null, "a", "b", "c", undefined, undefined, NaN, NaN]
```

This aligns more closely to the sorting when comparing numbers as `null` is seen as `0`.
Regardless, in your own code you'll want to run a `_.compact` on your results to remove the empties.

Could you tweak the PR to align with this and add/augment a test for the other sortBy-like methods.

This will sort the following values at the end and in the order of `null`, `undefined`, `NaN`.

``` js
var sorted = _.sortBy([Infinity, null, -1, NaN, 2, undefined, 3]);
// => [-1, 1, 2, 3, Infinity, null, undefined, NaN]

_.dropRightWhile(sorted, _.negate(_.isFinite));
// => [-1, 1, 2, 3]
```

