Yeah, this is a bad idea for the reasons @StreetStrider states. It is also misnamed (should be "isThenable" not "isPromise"). It is also non-resilient in the face of things like

``` js
var sometimesThenable = {
  get then() { return Math.random() > 0.5 ? function () { } : "not a function"; }
};
```

and encourages a bad coding pattern of

``` js
if (_.isThenable(sometimesThenable)) {
  sometimesThenable.then(...);
}
```

instead of the more correct one of

``` js
var then = sometimesThenable.then;
if (typeof then === "function") {
  then.call(sometimesThenable, ...);
}
```

Here's [Bluebird](https://github.com/petkaantonov/bluebird) example:

``` javascript
Promise.resolve(value).then(...)
```

If `value` is not a promise it will be casted to promise, and `then` is used. If it's already a promise it will be passed through. I think this is a good pattern.
On the other hand, the following one is antipattern:

``` javascript
if (isPromise(value)) {
  value.then(/* do something */);
} else {
  /* do something */
}
```

Here we need to duplicate `do something` or move it to function. In contrast, in first example we need to `do something` in one place at all.

@ajwhite, I think there are many great instruments (like Bluebird, Q) which handles Promises/A+ perfectly. LoDash works great with collections. So there's no practical need to implement such stuff here.

``` javascript
var Q = require('bluebird');
Q.resolve(value);
Q.reject(value);
```

