_.map(['one', 'two', 'one'], _.partial(_.result, object));
```

OK you're right. But i think it can make `_.values` more flexible, especially when it calls with a callback function (like `_.pick`).
Or when an invalid key would requested:

``` javascript
var object = { one: 1, two: 2 };

_.map(['one', 'two', 'four', 'one'], function(key) {
  return object[key];
});
// => [1, 2, undefined, 1]

_.map(['one', 'two', 'four', 'one'], _.partial(_.result, object));
// => [1, 2, undefined, 1]
```

But the suggested `_.values`:

``` javascript
_.values({ one: 1, two: 2 }, 'one', 'two', 'four', 'one');
// => [1, 2, 1]
```

While it's backward compatible:

``` javascript
_.values({ one: 1, two: 2 });
// => [1, 2]
```

